solutions.content:
**Data Structure**

DP 1D array: `int[] M = new int[n]` where `M[i]` represents the max profit ending at day `i`

---
**Logic**

We will focus on current day `i`, what kind of day it is? 3 cases: 
1. buy day
2. cooldown day
3. sell day

We will discuss each one of them
1. If it is a buy day, then we cannot make any profit at current day, so the max profit is the max profit we have made previously, i.e. yesterday, `M[i] = M[i - 1]`    
2. If It is a cooldown day, then same as above, we cannot make profit at current day =>`M[i] = M[i - 1](1)` 
3. If It is a sell day, then which day is the buy day? The `buy day` could be any days before day `i`(exclusive, i.e. `0` to `i - 1`). Let's denote it as `j`, then the profit we get = `+ previous day's profit + nums[i] - nums[j]`. The problem becomes what is the  `previous days' profit`? To figure it out, ask youself what about the day `j - 1`?
3.1. `j - 1` **cannot** be a buy day. Since you cannot have 2 continuous days(`j - 1` and `j`) as the `buy day`, you must sell the stock before you buy again as required.
3.2. `j - 1` **cannot** be a sell day as well, because if it is, day `j` must be a cooldown day.
3.3. Thus, day `j - 1` must be a cooldown day. If it is a cooldown day, then the max profit we can get at day `j - 1` is `M[j - 2]`
Above all, **`M[i] = Math.max(M[j - 2] + nums[i] - nums[j]) for j = 0 to i - 1 (2)`**

With **(1)** and **(2)**, we know that:
`M[i] = max(M[i - 1], Math.max(M[j - 2] + nums[i] - nums[j]) for j = 0 to i - 1)`

---
**Naive solution** (DP: linear scan backwards)

time complexity: `O(n^2)`
space complexity: `O(n)`

**Final Code**

```java
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        if(prices == null || prices.length == 0) return 0;

        int n = prices.length;
        int[] M = new int[n];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(i == 0) M[0] = 0;
            else if(i == 1) M[1] = Math.max(prices[1] - prices[0], 0);
            else{
                M[i] = M[i - 1];
                // linear scan
                for(int j = 0; j < i; j++){
                    int prev = j >= 2 ? M[j - 2] : 0;
                    M[i] = Math.max(M[i], prev + prices[i] - prices[j]);
                }
            }
        }

        return M[n - 1];
    }
}
```

---

**Optimized Solution**

time complexity: `O(n)`
space complexity: `O(n)`

If you notice that: **`M[i] = max(M[i - 1], Math.max(M[j - 2] + nums[i] - nums[j]) for j = 0 to i - 1)`(3)**

`M[j - 2] + nums[i] - nums[j]` can be transformed `(M[j - 2] - nums[j]) + nums[i]`, and `M[j - 2] - nums[j]` is the only variable changing. Then if we keep a varible(`maxDiff`) to keep track of the max of it, **(3)** can be changed to **`M[i] = max(M[i - 1], maxDiff + nums[i]) for j = 0 to i - 1)`(4)**

**Final Code**

```java
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        if(prices == null || prices.length == 0) return 0;

        int n = prices.length;
        int[] M = new int[n];
        int maxDiff = Integer.MIN_VALUE; // M[j - 2] - prices[j]
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(i < 2) maxDiff = Math.max(maxDiff, -prices[i]);
            if(i == 0) M[0] = 0;
            else if(i == 1) M[1] = Math.max(prices[1] - prices[0], 0);
            else{
                M[i] = Math.max(M[i - 1], maxDiff + prices[i]);
                maxDiff = Math.max(maxDiff, M[i - 2] - prices[i]);
            }
        }

        return M[n - 1];
    }
}
```

---
**One more thing**

If you have any confusion or any opinion on the desciption, please comment. I will insist on updating it for **at least 100 years**.

