solutions.content:
At a given day, we should take the maximum between:
* profit today + profit yesterday (assuming our stock grows well)
* profit the day before yesterday (assuming our stock has dropped, so the better idea might be to sell it the day before yesterday and have a cooldown yesterday).

You can also think of it as being greedy until you get in trouble. Then you travel back in time and sell it for a better price.

There are four key cases pictured below.

1. The stock grows well, so we take profits day-to-day:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/yelizarov/image_1583717359.png)
2. The stock dropped, so we look back for a better deal:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/yelizarov/image_1583717442.png)
3. The stock dropped, so we look back for a better deal, but there's none of them:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/yelizarov/image_1583717532.png)
4. The stock has dropped on the last trading day. This is the case to explain the need of the last `return Max` statement, so we take the previous day's profit (3), not the last one (2):
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/yelizarov/image_1583717826.png)

Here's a pretty self-explanatory code:
```
    public int MaxProfit(int[] prices) 
    {
      if (prices == null)
      {
        return 0;
      }

      int profitYesterday = 0;
      int profitBeforeYesterday = 0;

      for (int i = 1; i < prices.Length; i++)
      {
        var priceToday = prices[i];
        var priceYesterday = prices[i - 1];
        var profitToday = priceToday - priceYesterday;
        var maxProfitToday = Math.Max(profitToday + profitYesterday, profitBeforeYesterday);

        profitBeforeYesterday = Math.Max(profitYesterday, profitBeforeYesterday);
        profitYesterday = maxProfitToday;
      }

      return Math.Max(profitYesterday, profitBeforeYesterday);
    }
