solutions.content:
Just ask yourself what are you trying to do here.

1. If I don't have a stock today, then I either sold a stock today or I am not buying any today.
	* If I am not buying,  `profitWithoutStock = profitWithoutStockYesterday`
	* If I sold a stock, `profitWithoutStock = profitWithStockYesterday + prices[i]`
	* So `profitWithoutStock = Math.Max(profitWithoutStockYesterday, profitWithStockYesterday+prices[i]);` 

2. I have a stock today, then either I am holding my stock from yesterday or I bought a stock today.
	* If I am holding, `profitWithStock = profitWithStockYesterday`
	* If I bought a stock, then because of the 1-day cooldown,  `profitWithStock = profitWithoutStockDayBeforeYesterday - prices[i]`
	* So `profitWithStock = Math.Max(profitWithStockYesterday, profitWithoutStockDayBeforeYesterday-prices[i]);`

On the first day, `profitWithStock = -prices[0]` and `profitWithoutStock = 0`

The final result is `profitWithoutStock`.

All the lines above translated into code below :)

``` csharp
public class Solution {
    public int MaxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.Length;

		var profitWithoutStock = 0;
        var profitWithoutStockYesterday = 0;
        var profitWithoutStockDayBeforeYesterday = 0;

        var profitWithStock = 0;
        var profitWithStockYesterday = -prices[0];

        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){
			// As expained in 1 and 2
            profitWithoutStock = Math.Max(profitWithoutStockYesterday, profitWithStockYesterday+prices[i]);
            profitWithStock = Math.Max(profitWithStockYesterday, profitWithoutStockDayBeforeYesterday-prices[i]);

			// Reassign variables for the next iteration
            profitWithoutStockDayBeforeYesterday = profitWithoutStockYesterday;
            profitWithoutStockYesterday = profitWithoutStock;
            profitWithStockYesterday = profitWithStock;
        }

        return profitWithoutStock;
    }
}
```

