### 	Approach
	As per the question, we will always either - buy stock, or sell stock, or stay in cooldown (no stock in hand) for atleast one day.

    So, each day We will have 3 states:
        a. noStock  (or day when you have Cooldown)
        b. in-Hand  (or day when you buy)
        c. sold     (or day when you sell)

    For each of these states, we will calculate maximum profit. 

    Try to understand below: 
    a. noStock = maximum of (previous noStock, previous  sold) 
    b. inHand  = maximum of (previous inHand, previous noStock - price on current day)
    c. sold  =  previous inHand + price on current day

    We will use above 3 formulas to calculate maximum profit in each state, everyday.

### Dry-Run:
			i =      0      1       2       3       4 

	  prices =      [1,     2,      3,      0,      2]           // value of a stock on each day starting at index 0

	  noStock =     0       0       1       2       2 
	  inHand  =    -1      -1      -1       1       1
	  sold    =     0       1       2      -1       3

	  => max Profit = maximum of (2, 3)     // we compare only 2 & 3 and not 2,1,3. Because there is no point to consider profit value from inHand state. 

###  Complexity:
	Time:  O(n)
	Space: O(1)   // because instead of creating 3 arrays for noStock, inHand & sold, we just used 3 variables.


### Code:

	class Solution {
		public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
			int n=prices.length;
			if(n < 2) return 0;        

			int noStock = 0, inHand = 0 - prices[0], sold = 0;                               // initialize these 3 variables

			for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){
				int temp_noStock = Math.max(noStock, sold);                                //  Check code explanation under "Approach"  
				int temp_inHand  = Math.max(inHand, noStock - prices[i]);
				int temp_sold  =  inHand + prices[i];

				noStock = temp_noStock; 
				inHand = temp_inHand; 
				sold  = temp_sold;
			}

			return Math.max(noStock, sold);                      
		}

	}

