solutions.content:
You must be very confused how the most votes answers came up with the method with `O(n)` time complexity. Those guys must be genius! 
But I guess the first answer occured in their mind was probably straighforward and rough. 

Follow this answer, you will learn the thinking process step by step from the straighforward method to the intelligent one.


First, probably most of you can come up with an `O(2^n)` method:
```java
// O(2^n)
public int maxProfitRange(int[] prices, int start, int end) {
		// start: start day, end: end day
        if(start >= end) return 0;
        int res = 0;
		// Profit(start, end) = Max(Profit(buy on day start, end), Profit(not buy on day start, end))
        res = Math.max(res, maxProfitRange(prices, start+1, end));
        for(int i = start+1; i<end;i++){
            res = Math.max(res, prices[i]-prices[start] + maxProfitRange(prices, i+2, end));
        }
        return res;
    }
	public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
		return maxProfitRange(prices, 0, prices.length);
	}
```

Let me explain a little bit here. On each day, you have many choices, buy or not buy, sell or not sell. We should split this problem into two subproblems: 1. buy on that day. 2. not buy on that day. That is `Profit(start, end) = Max(Profit(buy on day start, end), Profit(not buy on day start, end))`

It is easy to know that `Profit(not buy on day start, end)) = Profit(start+1, end) `.

For `Profit(buy on day start, end)`, the problem becomes to decide which day to sell will make the profit max. Let's iterate every day after the buy day and check whether sell on this day will be best. That is `Profit(buy on day start, end) = for each day i>start, find the max(prices[i]-prices[start] + Profit(start+2, end))` (start+2 since we need cooldown 1 day)

The time complexity of this answer is `O(2^n)`. Because we calculate the same value many times. Let's use Dynamic Programming to reduce the time complexity to `O(n^2)`

```java
// O(n^2)
public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int length = prices.length;
        int[] dp = new int[prices.length+2];
        for(int start = length-1; start>=0;start--){
			// Profit(start, end) = Max(Profit(buy on day start, end), Profit(not buy on day start, end))
            dp[start] = dp[start+1];
			// redundant
            for(int sell=start+1;sell<length;sell++){
                dp[start] = Math.max(dp[start], prices[sell]-prices[start]+dp[sell+2]);
            }
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
```

The idea is that we save the calculated value into an dp array, so next time we don't need to calculate it again but only loop up the array.

But there are still some redundant calculations. For example, for every start day, we need to calculate  `Math.max(dp[start], prices[sell]-prices[start]+dp[sell+2]);` Why not just save the max `prices[sell] + dp[sell+2])`, and update this `max_sell` every time? If we do this, the code becomes:

```java
// O(n)
public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int length = prices.length;
        int[] dp = new int[prices.length+2];
        int max_sell = 0;
        for(int start = length-1; start>=0;start--){
            dp[start] = Math.max(dp[start+1], max_sell - prices[start]);
            max_sell = Math.max(max_sell, prices[start]+dp[start+2]);
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
```

The time complexity is reduced to `O(n)`, but the space complexity is also `O(n)`. Can we reduce the space complexity to `O(1)`?
Yes, just use another variable `res_prev` to store the dp[start+2] and update it every time.

```java
public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int max_sell = 0, res = 0, res_prev = 0;
        for(int start = prices.length-1; start>=0;start--){
            max_sell = Math.max(max_sell, prices[start]+res_prev);
            res_prev = res;
            res = Math.max(res, max_sell - prices[start]);
        }
        return res;
    }
```

Done!

