solutions.content:
At each timestamp `i`, there are 3 states: 
(1) you have stock in hands;
(2) you just sold at `i` and  cannot buy at `i+1`; 
(3) you don't have stock and can buy at `i+1`.

The next step is to find their relationship:
(1) you can buy this stock at `i` or before `i`, which corresponds to `dp[i-1][2]-prices[i]` and `dp[i-1][0]` respectively. (Buying is viewed as a negative profit)
(2) You own stock at `i-1` and sell at `i`, so now you have `dp[i-1][0] + prices[i]`.
(3) You sold your stock at `i-1` or before, which corresponds to `dp[i-1][1]` and `dp[i-1][2]` respectively.

Finally, just return the max of `dp.back()[1]` and `dp.back()[2]` since you can't get maximum profit if you still have stock in hands.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        if (prices.size() <= 1) return 0;
        vector<vector<int>> dp(prices.size(), vector<int>(3, -INT_MAX));
        dp[0][0] = -prices[0];
        dp[0][2] = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < prices.size(); i++) {
            dp[i][0] = max(dp[i-1][0], dp[i-1][2]-prices[i]); // have stock in hands
            dp[i][1] = dp[i-1][0] + prices[i]; // just sold stock at i
            dp[i][2] = max(dp[i-1][1], dp[i-1][2]); // don't have stock, able to buy at i+1
        }
        return max(dp.back()[1], dp.back()[2]);
    }
};
```

