Hello, after struggling nearly a day with this problem, I have finally managed to solve it. Understanding this problem was very difficult for me, so I wrote the solution below on a step by step basis, just the way I understood it. As a matter of fact, I wrote the comments first so that I could formulate the whole process of what is happening.

The trick in this problem is that at a specific day i, we can get three different values of profit because simply on day i, we can either buy, sell or hold the stock. The key is to keep that in mind, and solve for all possible actions (buy, sell hold) for a given day of the problem.

You may want to draw this [state transition image](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hot13399/leetcode-graphic-answer/master/Best%20Time%20to%20Buy%20and%20Sell%20Stock%20with%20Cooldown.jpg) on a page and work your way through the problem by hand at first.


```
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        if (prices.length == 0) {return 0;}
        int [] buy = new int [prices.length];
        int [] sell = new int [prices.length];
        int [] rest = new int [prices.length];

        // on day 0, default cases are:
        //   (i).   buy -> profit after buying stock on day 0 for prices[0]
        //   (ii).  sell -> profit after selling stock on day 0; since we may only buy on day 0, it is not possible to sell on day 0
        //   (iii). rest -> profit after not opting to buy/sell on day 0; hence, profit is 0
        buy[0] = - prices[0]; // when we BUY, our profit is decreased by the price of the stock on that day
        sell[0] = 0; // when we SELL, our profit is increased by the price of stock on that day
        rest[0] = 0; // when we REST, our profit is the same as the previous day's profit after resting, or the previous day's profit after selling


        // i -> day [1 ... N]
        // price[i] -> price we buy/sell/hold/dontHold at day i
        for (int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++) {

            // let's say we have a stock in hand on day i
            // there are two ways to achieve that -> buying the stock on day i, or having bought the stock on a previous day
            // therefore, possible state transitions are: rest -> buy [on BUY] OR buy -> buy [on REST, that is holding the stock]
            // in the latter, no changes were made to the stock in hand
            buy[i] = Math.max(rest[i - 1] - prices[i], buy[i - 1]);

            // let's say we sold the stock in hand on day i
            // only one possible state transition of achieving that: buy -> sell [on SELL]
            sell[i] = buy[i - 1] + prices[i];

            // let's say we are in cooldown on day i
            // important point to note here is that, a day on cooldown means I can buy the stock the next day
			// this means, I need to maintain previous day's rest records here
            // once again, there are two ways of attaining that: 
            //   (i).  rest on day i after selling on previous day, i.e. day [i - 1]
            //   (ii). rest on day i by waiting multiple days after selling, i.e. having sold on a day BEFORE day [i - 1]
            // therefore, the transitions are: sell -> rest [on SELL] OR rest -> rest [on REST]
            rest[i] = Math.max(rest[i - 1], sell[i - 1]);
        }

        // After days [0 ... N] has elapsed, I want to find the maximum profit
        // So the final action that I must have taken may either be SELL or REST
        // If the final action has been a BUY, then my profit will only decrease.
        return Math.max(rest[prices.length - 1], sell[prices.length - 1]);
    }
}
```

Last but not the least, I have learned a lot from this discussion forum and without it, I would not have been able to develop the thought-process involving different states or actions. Hence, this is my way of returning the favor. **Feedbacks and constructive criticism are welcome :)**


