>Let `dp[i]` is the maximum profit you can get from `i`th day to the last day ( i.e in the subarray `{i,i+1,..n-1}`) 


 **SIMPLE AND DETAILED EXPLANATION OF THE LOGIC BEHIND THE IMPLEMENTATION**

The main idea behind this is that, when you are at `i`th day, since you want to find the maximum profit you can make from the subarray `{i,i+1,..n-1}`, so there are two possibilites in this, 
>In calculation of `dp[i]` it is not necessary that I buy the stock on `i`th day. There are two possibilities
>1) you don't buy the stock on the ith day
>2) You buy the stock on the ith day

For the 1st case, `dp[i]` will be equal to `dp[i+1]`.

For the 2nd case, when you buy the stock on `i`th day, you will sell it on some `j`th day, then the profit you will make is `prices[j] + dp[j+2] - prices[i]`. 

But we don't quite already know on which day to sell it, so for every `j>=i` we want to know maximum of `prices[j] + dp[j+2]`.

So when you are at `i`, instead of finding this value for every `j`, you could maintain this value in one variable called `maxi` then for the 2nd case, the answer will be `maxi-prices[i]`.

**So out of the two cases, we want the maximum one, so dp[i]=max(dp[i+1], maxi-prices[i])**
Finally `dp[0]` is our answer

```
int n=prices.size();
int dp[n];    
dp[n-1]=0; // There is only one possibility. you buy it and sell it on the same day
int maxi=prices[n-1]; // maxi stores the maximum of prices[j]+dp[j+2] for all j>=i
for(int i=n-2;i>=0;i--)
{
	maxi=max(maxi,prices[i]+(i+2<n? dp[i+2]: 0));
	dp[i]=max(dp[i+1], maxi-prices[i]);
}
return dp[0];
```

