solutions.content:
**DP states definition**
```sell[i]``` as maximum profit we will obtain at time ```i``` if I force selling at ```price[i]```.
```rest[i]``` as maximum profit we will obtain at time ```i``` at which we must compromise on cooldown.
Note that we don't have to memorize any ```buy[i]``` states, since we are assuming that we will buy stocks at ```i+1``` moment after cooldown```rest[i]```. 

**Formula**
```
sell[i] = max ( sell[i-1] + profit, rest[i-2] + profit, 0 );
rest[i] = max ( sell[i-1], rest[i-1]);
```
**1. Sell**
At moment```i```, profit is defined as ```profit = price[i] - price[i-1]```. 
Maximum profit force selling at ```i``` is 
```
sell[i] = max ( sell[i-1] + profit, rest[i-2] + profit, 0 );
```
- Holding stocks and selling them all at moment ```i ```. 
```sell[i-1] + profit ```
- We've already sold off all the shares before moment ```i-2``` and paid off cooldown penalty at ```i-2```. 
So that we can purchase at ```price[i-1]``` and sell them at ```price[i] ```. 
```rest[i-2] + profit```.
- We will lose money whatsoever, rollbacking all previous transaction. In this case, it implies that we start a fresh new trade with zero profit.
```0```.

**2. Rest**
At moment```i```, we're either in cooldown or in rest. So our maximum profit could be obtained by 
- Selling stocks at ```i-1```. So max profit could be ```sell[i-1]```
- Inherited from previous rest moment. Max profit could be   ```rest[i-1]```
```
rest[i] = max ( sell[i-1], rest[i-1]);
```

It takes me hours to tackle this problem, from a brute force recursion solution to ```O(n^2)``` Time ```O(n)``` Space.
After several optimizations, I finally came up with the code here. Instead of interpreting the buy and sell as state machines, my solution focus more on intuitive bottom-up DP.

```O(n)``` Time and ```O(n)``` Space, with ```sell``` and ```rest``` memorizing states
```
public class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        if(prices.length < 2) return 0;
        int n = prices.length, max;
        int[] sell = new int[n];
        int[] rest = new int[n];

        sell[0] = 0;
        sell[1] = Math.max(prices[1] - prices[0], 0);
        for(int i = 2; i < sell.length; i++){            
            int profit = prices[i]-prices[i-1];
            sell[i] = Math.max(Math.max( sell[i-1], rest[i-2] ) + profit, 0);
            rest[i] = Math.max(sell[i-1], rest[i-1]);
        }
        return  Math.max(sell[n-1], rest[n-1]);
    }
}
```

```O(n)``` Time and ```O(1)``` Space.
```
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        if(prices.length < 2) return 0;

        for(int i = prices.length-1; i > 0; i--) 
            prices[i] = prices[i] - prices[i-1];

        int sell = 0, prevSell = Math.max(prices[1], 0), cooldown = 0, prevCooldown = 0;  

        for(int i = 2; i < prices.length; i++){            
            int close = prices[i];
            sell = Math.max( prevSell, prevCooldown) + close;
            sell = Math.max( sell, 0);

            prevCooldown = cooldown;
            cooldown = Math.max(prevSell, cooldown);
            prevSell = sell;
        }
        return Math.max(prevSell, cooldown);
    }
```



**Below are my very beginning thoughts on this problem. Feel free to skip it if you already understand my idea above.**

My first thought was to try every possible combination of ```rest``` and ```profit``` that sells at ```i``` which take ```O(n^2)``` time. 
(*Note that ```profit[1 - 2] = price[2] - price[1]```*)
```
sell[0] = 0; 
sell[1] = max ( profit[0 - 1], 0);
sell[2] = max ( profit[0 - 2], rest[0] + profit[1 - 2]);
sell[3] = max ( profit[0 - 3], rest[0] + profit[1 - 3], rest[1] + profit[2 - 3]);
sell[4] = max ( profit[0 - 4], rest[0] + profit[1 - 4], rest[1] + profit[2 - 4], rest[2] + profit[3 - 4]);
...
sell[i] = max ( profit[0 - i], rest[0] + profit[1 - i], rest[1] + profit[2 - i], ..., rest[i-1] + profit[i-1 - i]);
```
As you might have observed, there are connections between those ```sell[i]```.

Lets take ```sell[2]``` and ```sell[3]``` as example,
```
sell[2] = max ( profit[0 - 2], rest[0] + profit[1 - 2]);
```
```
sell[3] = max ( profit[0 - 3], rest[0] + profit[1 - 3], rest[1] + profit[2 - 3] ) 
        = max ( profit[0 - 2] + profit[2 - 3], rest[0] + profit[1 - 2] + profit[2 - 3], rest[1] + profit[2 - 3]
```
- The first two terms in ```sell[3]```: 
```profit[0 - 2] + profit[2 - 3], rest[0] + profit[1 - 2] + profit[2 - 3]``` can be reduce to 
```sell[2] + profit[2 - 3]```. 
- Hence, ```sell[3]``` can be rewritten as: 
``` max ( sell[2] + profit[2 - 3], rest[1] + profit[2 - 3] ) ```
- By factoring ```profit[2 - 3]``` out of the equation we will have:
 ``` max ( sell[2] , rest[1] ) + profit[2 - 3] );```
- Generalizing this pattern: 
```sell[i] = max ( sell[i-1], rest[i-2] ) + profit[i-1 - i] );```
- One more case to consider: In selling cases that will leads to negative profit, for example ```[5, 1] ```, because by definition ```sell[i]``` represent the max profit that force selling at ```i``` moment, maximum profit ```sell[i]``` can only be ```0```.
- Adding all cases up:
```sell[i] = max ( sell[i-1], rest[i-2] ) + profit[i-1 - i], 0)```

public class Solution {
    public int MaxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int[] result = new int[prices.Length];
        int[] sell = new int[prices.Length];

        for(int i = 1; i < prices.Length; i++) {
            var diff = prices[i] - prices[i-1];
            sell[i] = diff + Math.Max(sell[i-1], i > 2 ? result[i-3] : 0);
            result[i] = Math.Max(sell[i], result[i-1]);
        }

        return result.Length == 0 ? 0 : result[result.Length-1];
    }
}

