solutions.content:
Basically, we have 2 possible states at any index ```i``` as follow -:
State 1. We don't have any stock -> Possible options to move forward is to either buy a stock today or on a later date.
State 2. We have a stock -> Possible options to move forward from this state is to either sell today and then move forward with State 1 from ```(i+2)th``` index, or to sell the stock on a later date.

Here is the solution I have coded usign above scenarios. The parameter ```bought``` represents whether or not you own a stock when reaching the ith index.
1. ```bought``` value 1 represents we own a stock
2. ```bought``` value 0 represent we do not own a stock

Remember, if you chosse to buy the stock on ith day, the total profit will be ```prices[selling_day_index] - prices[i]```, the same has been implemented usign ```(-1) * prices[i]```

```
class Solution {
public:
    int stock(vector<int>& prices, vector<vector<int>> &dp, int bought, int i, int n) {
        if (i >= n) {
            return 0;
        }
        if (dp[i][bought] != -1) {
            return dp[i][bought];
        }
        if (bought) {
            dp[i][bought] = max(prices[i] + stock(prices, dp, 0, i+2, n), stock(prices, dp, 1, i+1, n));
        } else {
            dp[i][bought] = max(-1*prices[i] + stock(prices, dp, 1, i+1, n), stock(prices, dp, 0, i+1, n));
        }
        return dp[i][bought];
    }
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int n = prices.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int> (2, -1));
        if (n == 1) {
            return 0;
        }
        return max(0, stock(prices, dp, 0, 0, n));
    }
};
```

Time Complexity : ```O(n)``` since we only swap the array twice at most
Space Complexity :```O(n)``` since we create a DP array with fixed number of columns which is ```2```, i.e. space used is ```2 * (n)```, i.e. ```O(n)```

