solutions.content:
Step1: Define DP

	DP[i][j] , i : days ; j : if hold stock

	DP[3][0] --> at 3th day and not hold stock, the max profit would be DP[3][0]; 

	DP[3][1] --> at 3th day and  hold stock, the max profit would be DP[3][1]; 

Step2: Find the formula that induct DP[i][j]

	a. One tranzaction one time.  So guess where DP[i][0] come from? the answer are   DP[i-1][0] or DP[i-1][1] ---->> So,

		DP[i][0] = max( DP[i-1][0], DP[i-1][1] + prices[i] );


	b. There must exit at least cooldown day before buy the stock. So guess where DP[i][1] come from?  the answer are : DP[i-1][1] or DP[i-2][0].

	   DP[i][1] = max( DP[i-1][1], DP[i-2][0] - prices[i] );

	   Notice:  if i <2,  DP[i][1] = max( DP[i-1][1],  - prices[i] );    The reason is that when i <2, we don't need to consider cooldown time.


Solution:
```

class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {

        // dp[ days ][ holdstatus ], status: 0 -> not hold, 1 -> hold

        if(prices.empty()) return 0;

        int n = prices.size();
        vector< vector<int> > dp( n, vector<int>(2,0) );

        dp[0][0] = 0;
        dp[0][1] = -prices[0];

        for( int i = 1 ; i < n ; i++ ){


            dp[i][0] = max( dp[i-1][0], dp[i-1][1] + prices[i] );

            dp[i][1] =  dp[i-1][1];

            if( i-2>=0 )
                dp[i][1] = max( dp[i][1], dp[i-2][0] - prices[i] );
            else
                dp[i][1] = max( dp[i][1], -prices[i] );


        }

        return max( {dp[n-1][0], dp[n-1][1]} );

    }
};

```

