**Idea? Dp on Trees with Rerooting**
* Let's understand the problem in simpler words.*Consider D1,D2,...Dn is the maximum depth of tree rooted at node Di. We need to find min(D1, D2,...Dn). Then, find all those nodes which give this minimum Value*.
* The Basic Approach is to consider every node as the root node and find the maximum depth of the tree, store it in the vector of pairs and find those nodes which correspond to the minimum maximum depth of the tree. It will cost **O(n^2) time which won't give AC**. **How do we optimize our code?** **Can we answer the maximum depth of tree for the current root node without running dfs again?**
* Yes, We can find that.
**Steps:-**
* **Root the Tree at any node** and find the maximum depth of every subtree (stored in vector h).
* Now, **Can we answer the maximum depth of tree when we consider v as the root node?**
* Yes.
* **Maximum depth [v] = 1 + max(par max upto node p,max(h[u])) for all u which is child of v**
* Note that when we move to child u of node v, par max for child u changes.
* **par max for child u will be max(par max of node v,max(h[t])) for all t not equal to u.**
* Check code for a detailed explanation.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/601cec6c-43cd-43ac-a1f6-067baae6c992_1639638364.554435.png)


```
class Solution {
public:
    // Time Complexity:- O((V+E)log(V))
    // Space Complexity:- O(V)
    int MHT = INT_MAX; // Minimum Height, considering every node as root
    vector<int> ans; // stores all MHTs
    void dfs(int v,int p,vector<int> adj[],vector<int>& h){
        // h[v] = maximum depth of subtree of v
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p){
                dfs(u,v,adj,h);
                h[v] = max(h[v],h[u]);
            }
        }
        h[v]++;
    }
    void dfs(int v,int p,vector<int> adj[],vector<int>& h,int par_max){
        // par_max stores maximum height of subtree of p when v is the child of p
        // multiset stores maximum height of all child nodes when we consider v as root node
        multiset<int,greater<int>> mx = {par_max};
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p)
                mx.insert(h[u]);
        }
        // 1 + *mx.begin() = maximum depth of tree if v is the root node
        if(1+*mx.begin()<MHT){
            MHT = 1 + *mx.begin();
            ans.clear();
            ans.push_back(v);
        }
        else if(1+*mx.begin()==MHT)
            ans.push_back(v);
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p){
                // if we go to child u, we need to pass par_max
                // we should erase maximum height entry for subtree of u from multiset
                mx.erase(mx.find(h[u]));
                dfs(u,v,adj,h,1+*mx.begin());
                mx.insert(h[u]);
            }
        }
    }
    vector<int> findMinHeightTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        vector<int> adj[n],h(n);
        for(auto& edge:edges){
            adj[edge[0]].push_back(edge[1]);
            adj[edge[1]].push_back(edge[0]);
        }
        dfs(0,-1,adj,h); // find the maximum depth for every subtree considering root node as 0
        dfs(0,-1,adj,h,0); // finds all nodes which corresponds to MHT
        return ans;
    }
};
```

**Since we maximum at each time totally depends on maximum or second maximum element present in the multiset, we replace multiset by storing maximum and second maximum each time.**

```
class Solution {
public:
    // Time Complexity:- O(V+E)
    // Space Complexity:- O(V)
    int MHT = INT_MAX; // Minimum Height, considering every node as root
    vector<int> ans; // stores all MHTs
    void dfs(int v,int p,vector<int> adj[],vector<int>& h){
        // h[v] = maximum depth of subtree of v
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p){
                dfs(u,v,adj,h);
                h[v] = max(h[v],h[u]);
            }
        }
        h[v]++;
    }
    void dfs(int v,int p,vector<int> adj[],vector<int>& h,int par_max){
        // par_max stores maximum height of subtree of p when v is the child of p
        pair<int,int> mx = {par_max,0}; // first element = maximum, second element = second maximum
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p){
                if(h[u]>mx.first){
                    mx.second = mx.first;
                    mx.first = h[u];
                }
                else
                    mx.second = max(mx.second,h[u]);
            }
        }
        if(1+mx.first<MHT){
            MHT = 1 + mx.first;
            ans.clear();
            ans.push_back(v);
        }
        else if(1+mx.first==MHT)
            ans.push_back(v);
        for(auto& u:adj[v]){
            if(u!=p){
                // if we go to child u, we need to pass par_max
                // we should erase maximum height entry for subtree of u from multiset
                int curr = (h[u]==mx.first)?mx.second:mx.first;
                dfs(u,v,adj,h,1+curr);
            }
        }
    }
    vector<int> findMinHeightTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        vector<int> adj[n],h(n);
        for(auto& edge:edges){
            adj[edge[0]].push_back(edge[1]);
            adj[edge[1]].push_back(edge[0]);
        }
        dfs(0,-1,adj,h); // find the maximum depth for every subtree considering root node as 0
        dfs(0,-1,adj,h,0); // finds all nodes which corresponds to MHT
        return ans;
    }
};
```
**Alternate Approach**
* **Answer will be at most 2 vertices? Why?**
* For a tree, it has almost two centers and from centers, we will have maximum depth being minimized.
* **For an odd number of nodes, there will be only one cente**r.
* **For an even number of nodes, there will be two centers.**
* How to find all center nodes of a tree?
* Start Plucking Leaves of the tree one by one, finally you will end with nodes having centers.
* How to do that?, **Hint:- Degree of leaves = 1 in an undirected graph.**

```
class Solution {
public:
    // Time Complexity:- O(V+E)
    // Space Complexity:- O(V)
    vector<int> findMinHeightTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        if(n==1)
            return {0};
        vector<int> deg(n),adj[n];
        for(auto& edge:edges){
            adj[edge[0]].push_back(edge[1]);
            adj[edge[1]].push_back(edge[0]);
            deg[edge[1]]++;deg[edge[0]]++;
        }

        queue<int> q;
        vector<int> ans;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(deg[i]==1){ // start with leaves
                deg[i]--;
                q.push(i);
            }
        }

        while(!q.empty()){
            int sz = q.size();
            ans.clear();
            while(sz--){
                int v = q.front();
                q.pop();

                ans.push_back(v);
                for(auto& u:adj[v]){
                    if(--deg[u]==1) // when the current node becomes a leaf push it into queue
                        q.push(u);
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
